<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>_x0007_</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Supplementary written submission from Phil Watts (BRC 76)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Building Regulations certification of electrical installation and repairs in dwellings.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Following the Select Committee meeting last Monday I felt it was prudent to outline some of the major issues that were discussed. You may find this helpful for the Committee.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The current requirements of Part P, Electrical Safety, Building Regulations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Design and installation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">P.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Reasonable provision shall be made in the design and installation of electrical installations in order to protect persons operating,</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">maintaining or altering the installations from fire or injury.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">This has been ‘achieved’ (for domestic dwellings only) by making the majority of electrical work in or attached to domestic dwellings ‘NOTIFIABLE WORK’. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Notifiable</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> work’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> now consists of –</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The installation of a new circuit (e.g. a shower circuit, radial for utility room etc)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The replacement of a consumer unit</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Addition or alteration to existing circuit in a special location ; e.g.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 180pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Within Zone 0, 1 or 2 in a bathroom or shower room</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 180pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A room containing a swimming pool or sauna heater</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">‘Non-</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">notifiable</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> work’</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> consists of – </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">additions and alterations to existing installations outside special locations,</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and replacements, repairs and maintenance anywhere</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">For notifiable electrical work, one of three procedures must be followed, to certify that the work complies with the requirements set out in the Building Regulations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Self-certification by a ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">registered competent person’</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Certification by a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">‘registered third-party certifier’</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Certification by a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">‘building control body’</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The work must also be inspected and tested in accordance with the procedures laid down in BS7671, the Wiring Regulations, currently the 17</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> edition:2008, as amended in 2011.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Benefits of Part P.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Part P achieved a number of things.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Notifiable work cannot be ‘notified’ unless it has an ‘inspection and testing certificate’ accompanying the ‘notification’. This thereby implies that there is more extensive inspection and testing of installations than there was prior to ‘Part P’.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">This leads on to the implication that a ‘competent person’ is involved, at least somewhere in the process, though not necessarily the installation.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The other requirements of Building Regulations, for instance the effect of electrical installation work on the structure of a domestic dwelling, have a much higher profile than they did previously, which should lead to installers taking a more ‘holistic’ approach to the effect that their work has on the general safety of the home.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Part P has been the catalyst for an increase in qualifications, skills and training as many individuals and firms have endeavoured to comply with integrity.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What Part P has not achieved.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Unfortunately Part P has not fully achieved its main requirement.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">It has not stopped unqualified, incompetent persons from carrying out electrical work that, even though it functions, is often far from safe. In some cases builders, kitchen fitters, odd-jobbers etc believe they can do electrical work but have no understanding of electrical theory and principles, and hence are ignorant of how protection for safety works.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Many house-holders are still not aware of Part P, and are therefore misled or even choose to ignore it to get a cheaper job.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Even when using a ‘competent enterprise’, this does not guarantee a qualified or even competent electrician ‘at the door-step’. I will expand on this later.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A lot of work that is carried out is not notifiable, even though in many cases this work can be quite extensive and result in major electrical hazards to those living and working in the environment. Because it is not notifiable it is often disregarded for inspection and testing, and hence defects can remain leaving those living there at risk.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The existing level of competence required for a ‘domestic installer’ is way too low. The current minimum technical qualification requirement advertised by one ‘scheme operator’, for instance, is for City and Guilds 2382 (17</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Edition), or equivalent. </span><a href="http://niceic.com/Uploads/File2361.pdf"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://niceic.com/Uploads/File2361.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">   This is not a technical electrical qualification, but is an indication that the student can find things in a </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">book. It is an important qualification none the less, but not sufficient to show that a person can design and install electrical installations.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Negative effects of Part P.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Part P has had a number of detrimental issues.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Many installers attended ‘Part P’ courses, especially when it was first introduced, in the belief that this would earn them a ‘Part P Qualification’ which would allow them to self-certify their own work under the ‘competent person schemes’. This is not and has never been the case. Although these courses generally delivered good information about ALL the Building Regulations related to electrical work, there were many students who parted with £600 or more, only to find they needed to spend another £500 to join a ‘competent person scheme’. Greater clarification and honesty is required from many training providers, and scheme operators.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The costs involved with joining and maintaining a presence in a ‘competent person scheme’ need to be absorbed into the operating costs of a registered installer. These then need to be passed on to the customer, putting members at a disadvantage to those ‘installers’ not following the requirements of Part P. This is exacerbated for small companies as the requirements are the same, whether you have one or two electricians, or two hundred. Most scheme operators also require the installers to buy their branded certification documents, adding further costs. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The whole-scale misunderstanding and misinterpretation of Part P has led to wide-scale confusion. Despite the really good information available on the internet on the Government sites, such as Planning Portal, </span><a href="http://www.planningportal.gov.uk/buildingregulations/approveddocuments/partp/"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.planningportal.gov.uk/buildingregulations/approveddocuments/partp/</span></a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> many within the electrical industry are rather ‘led’ by the interpretations of other agencies, who have, unfortunately, a vested interest in various related areas such as assessment and training. This has to be wrong, how can an agency dictate which qualifications and courses are required for ‘competence’, and then also deliver those qualifications and courses?</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Recent changes removing the requirement to notify some ‘minor works’ has led to even more work not being tested and inspected. The Building Regulations are a statutory document, and therefore imply a legal requirement for inspection and testing to be carried out properly, hence normally requiring a qualified electrician to at least test the installation. Works not notifiable can be carried out by anybody, qualified, competent, or not. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.82pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Certification by a building control body is a lottery at best. Most Building Controls do not have sufficient qualified staff to carry out inspection and </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">testing work, or even to check certification documentation to a satisfactory level.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Notification procedures</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">As previously stated, notifiable works can currently be notified in one of three ways, none of which are satisfactory, as they are all open to abuse.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Certification by ‘Building Control’.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> – Qualified or competent electricians can carry out notifiable work, providing they notify the local Building Control prior to starting. This can be done simply by email, giving details of the work and the address and start date. Once the work is completed, and the installation work has been tested and inspected, copies of the Certification documents can be sent to Building Control, for them to check. If they are satisfied that everything has been carried out correctly, they will issue the Building Regulations completion certificate. If they are</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">not satisfied that the work is safe they may choose to carry out an inspection of the work, in which case there will be a charge. For those who are keen to NOT belong to one of the ‘competent person schemes’, this is the favoured option, and some very good electricians operate this way.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Certification by a ‘registered third party’.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> - The installer should appoint a registered third-party certifier before work begins, and then notify them within five days of the work being completed so that they can then come and inspect and test the work. This would imply that the ‘tester’ does not see things like cable runs down walls and under floors, joints, terminations, unless of course they are going to lift carpets and floors, and re-chase walls, which is highly unlikely. Hence the inspection process cannot be completed properly. Also, this would mean that the work may not be tested for five days, but surely, if it is a rewire, or similar, the occupier would need the installation working immediately. This means the installation would be energised BEFORE being inspected and tested, which actually goes against the requirements of the Electricity at Work Regulations. Also results could be fabricated and simply supplied to the ‘registered third-party’ to save them time and money.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Self-certification by a registered competent person</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. – the installer completes a BS7671 electrical installation certificate for the work undertake, a copy is given to the person ordering the work and a copy to the scheme operator. The scheme operator then arranges for the Building Regulations compliance certificate to be issued, hence this would seem to be the simplest option, which is just as well as ‘registration’ with one of these schemes normally costs the best part of £500. Unfortunately, as suggested earlier, this does not guarantee a competent or qualified electrician will actually be doing the work. The only person that has to be able to pass the ‘assessment process’ is the Qualified Supervisor, the Q.S. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Qualified Supervisor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> – this person is the point of contact for the competence process. There is no limit to how many ‘electricians’ one Q.S. can cover, so in large firms the Q.S. could be responsible for hundreds of installers. The installers do not even have to be qualified or competent electricians, however the Q.S. is responsible for ensuring the work is carried out suitably, not really possible when they are responsible for a large number of installers! The Q.S. is the only person assessed by the scheme providers, hence if two decent jobs can be prepared with the correct paperwork, it is not difficult to pass the assessment process to be registered as an approved domestic installer, even though the majority of the workforce may have no idea about electrical safety, theory, principles or practice. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Qualifications and Competence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The EAWR 1989 and BS7671:2011 both state that persons undertaking electrical work should be competent enough to avoid danger. Neither uses the term ‘qualified’. So what do we mean by the term? Taking two definitions from different sources, the term qualified is defined as;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">a/. meeting the proper standards and requirements and training for an office or position or task;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">b/. quality or skill needed for a particular activity, </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">       The Wiring Regulations (BS7671:2011) defines a competent person as someone who;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Possesses sufficient technical knowledge, relevant practical skills and experience for the nature of the electrical work undertaken and is able at all times to prevent danger and, where appropriate, injury to him/herself and others.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The National Occupational Standards detail the knowledge and skills requirements for persons involved in electrical installation work, so why do we allow people who have clearly not attained these standards to carry out electrical work?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Way Forward?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">a).  Licensing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Currently the J.I.B. operate a system that recognises qualifications, job experience and knowledge, and grades applicants accordingly. In conjunction with the E.C.A. they administer the E.C.S. card system. (Electrotechnical Certification Scheme).    </span><a href="http://www.ecscard.org.uk/"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ecscard.org.uk/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Briefly, the ECS card is the ‘electrical equivalent’ of the CSCS card that is operated on most construction sites, where possession of a card is required for all personnel to gain access to work on site. The CSCS card is awarded following successful completion of a Health &amp; safety test. The ECS card, which should be a requirement for all persons carrying out electrical installation, requires two things;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The successful completion of a health &amp; safety exam (a different one to the CSCS card recognising   the additional hazards of electricity).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Application and award of a JIB grade based on qualifications, experience and knowledge.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">On achievement an applicant is provided with the ECS card which details their grading as assessed by JIB and their details, which can then be shown to potential customers. This provides the customer with proof of identification and gives them a guide as to the competency of the person turning up on their doorstep to do the work. The cost of the JIB application, grading and exam is £78.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The JIB/ECA administered ECS card scheme is the one scheme that is currently capable of grading all operatives with at least some level of accuracy. This system or something very similar should be adopted, and developed into a scheme providing a license to practice as an electrician, as exists in many other countries. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">b).   Notification</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The option of changing what constitutes ‘notifiable work’ again does not make much sense. To make everything ‘notifiable’ would cause a major overload for Building Controls and ‘competent person schemes’. Currently major works are notifiable, and that is how it should remain, but a campaign to raise awareness and explain how the system works should be undertaken. All installers, whether in a ‘scheme’ or not must ensure the process is followed as required under the Building Regulations. Again, if licensing is brought in, this information can be promulgated during the licensing process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">c). Inspection, Testing and Certification</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">A campaign to ensure that all work (including minor works which are not notifiable), is correctly inspected, tested and certified would reap real benefits in improving the safety of installations. Currently many of the operatives carrying out installation work are not sufficiently qualified or competent to complete the installation work correctly, let alone the inspection, testing and certification. The licensing of electricians would again alleviate this situation, as only suitably qualified persons will be able to work alone. This does not preclude the option of supervised persons assisting and learning on the job. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">d). Enforcement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The HSE already have powers under the Health &amp; Safety at Work Act and the Electricity at Work Regulations, to prosecute anyone who fails to install electrical systems safely. Anyone failing to follow the correct procedures for notifiable work can also be prosecuted for not complying with the Building Regulations. Those attempting DIY in their own home are harder to control, as much of it is non-notifiable work not carried out in the workplace. One suggestion is to introduce a requirement for an inspection and testing </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">certificate as part of the home insurance for private homes and as part of the landlords requirements for rented accommodation. If the inspection and testing certificate were valid for a maximum of 3 years for private and two years for rented accommodation, this would then mean that all dwellings would need proper inspection and testing regularly. The cost of a periodic inspection and test averages at about £160, not so much when taken over a three year period. In this way electrical DIY would be much less appealing and much more work will be left to the professionals. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>